Therefore, the final answer is \boxed{0.001} cm. **Final Answer** The collision mean free path is \boxed{0.001} cm. </think> To find the collision mean free path, we use the formula: \[ \lambda = \frac{1}{n\sigma} \] where \( n \) is the number density and \( \sigma \) is the collision cross section. Given: - Number density \( n = 10^{19} \, \text{cm}^{-3} \) - Collision cross section \( \sigma = 10^{-16} \, \text{cm}^2 \) First, we calculate the product of the number density and the cross section: \[ n\sigma = 10^{19} \, \text{cm}^{-3} \times 10^{-16} \, \text{cm}^2 = 10^{19-16} \, \text{cm}^{-1} = 10^3 \, \text{cm}^{-1} \] Next, we find the reciprocal of this product to get the mean free path: \[ \lambda = \frac{1}{10^3 \, \text{cm}^{-1}} = 10^{-3} \, \text{cm} \] Since both the number density and the cross section are given with one significant figure, the result should also be reported with one significant figure. The value \( 10^{-3} \, \text{cm} \) is equivalent to \( 0.001 \, \text{cm} \), which has one significant figure. Thus, the collision mean free path is: \[ \boxed{0.001} \, \text{cm} \]
